<http://ns.inria.fr/iadas/sport-vocab/Thai_boxing> <http://ns.inria.fr/iadas/ontology/sportCategory> <http://ns.inria.fr/iadas/sport-category-vocab/Weight_class> .
<http://ns.inria.fr/iadas/sport-vocab/Thai_boxing> <http://purl.org/dc/terms/source> "Larousse" .
<http://ns.inria.fr/iadas/sport-vocab/Thai_boxing> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <http://ns.inria.fr/iadas/ontology/Sport> .
<http://ns.inria.fr/iadas/sport-vocab/Thai_boxing> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#Concept> .
<http://ns.inria.fr/iadas/sport-vocab/Thai_boxing> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#broader> <http://ns.inria.fr/iadas/sport-vocab/Martial_arts> .
<http://ns.inria.fr/iadas/sport-vocab/Thai_boxing> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#description> "A combat sport similar to American boxing, which allows elbow and knee strikes and is practised barefoot with gloves. Almost all blows are permitted; only blows to the head are prohibited. Among the techniques most commonly used are kicks to the neck, face and head, knee hooks to the ribs and kicks to the calves. In most matches, knee and elbow strikes win the decision. Boxers are divided into 16 weight categories. They compete in a 7.30 m2 ring surrounded by ropes held up by padded poles. A match follows a meticulous ritual. The match is preceded by the ram muay (the boxing dance), which is a tribute to the fighter's guru (khruu) and the guardian spirit of Thai boxing. " .
<http://ns.inria.fr/iadas/sport-vocab/Thai_boxing> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#inScheme> <http://ns.inria.fr/iadas/sport-category-vocab/Sport> .
<http://ns.inria.fr/iadas/sport-vocab/Thai_boxing> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#prefLabel> "Thai boxing" .
