<http://ns.inria.fr/iadas/sport-vocab/Trampoline_gymnastics> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <http://ns.inria.fr/iadas/ontology/Sport> .
<http://ns.inria.fr/iadas/sport-vocab/Trampoline_gymnastics> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#Concept> .
<http://ns.inria.fr/iadas/sport-vocab/Trampoline_gymnastics> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#broader> <http://ns.inria.fr/iadas/sport-vocab/Gymnastics> .
<http://ns.inria.fr/iadas/sport-vocab/Trampoline_gymnastics> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#description> "An acrobatic discipline that can be practiced individually or in pairs (called synchronized). Gymnasts perform on a trampoline measuring 4 meters by 2 meters, positioned 1.15 meters above the ground. 120 springs surrounding the trampoline allow the gymnasts to reach a height of up to 8 meters. The exercises consist of 10 trampoline touches, during which gymnasts can perform numerous acrobatic moves (jumps, flips, twists, etc.). These acrobatics must be performed in succession." .
<http://ns.inria.fr/iadas/sport-vocab/Trampoline_gymnastics> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#inScheme> <http://ns.inria.fr/iadas/sport-category-vocab/Sport> .
